Set ARCOS R Package API Key

For this exercise, we will be working with subsets of the DEAs ARCOS database, which documented shipments of 76 billion opioid pills between 2006 and 2012, during the peak of the opioid epidemic.

The data was obtained after a lengthy legal battle by the Washington Post and the Charleston Gazette-Mail, and released by the Washington Post in raw and aggregated form. Washington Post Digging into the DEAs pain pill database page.

A data dictionary is available here: ARCOS Registrant Handbook.

Were going to load opioid data exclusively from the arcos R package API ARCOS API produced by the Washington Post, instead of uploading csvs and tsvs.

Remember, we need to store a password of sorts called an API key that will give us permission to access their data. Heres a list of API keys that will work.

Store the key first.

# store one of our API keys as an object called key
key <- "uO4EK6I"

Load Data

Load the data youll need for this package and clean up the column names.

arcos_county_pills_per_year <- summarized_county_annual(key = key) %>%
  clean_names()

Build Exploratory Visualizations

Task: Build an exploratory visualization to show year-over-year pill totals in Logan County, West Virginia between 2006 and 2012. It should have the following attributes: * Chart Type: a bar chart, with one bar per year between 2006 and 2012. Make the bars forest green. * Axes: years on the x axis, pill totals on the y axis, with proper axis labels. The number for each year should be shown. Put commas in the pill totals on the y axis, so theyre readable.
* Text: put a descriptive title, subtitle and source line. The title should describe the main takeaway.

You should also write up a few sentences explaining the trend in a bit more detail.

# Create object that contains only Logan County data
logan_county_pills_per_year <- arcos_county_pills_per_year %>%
  filter(buyer_state == "WV", buyer_county == "LOGAN") %>%
  select(year, dosage_unit)
ggplot(logan_county_pills_per_year) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", aes(year, dosage_unit), fill="forest green") +
  labs(x="Year", y="Total pills", title="In Logan County, opioid shipments remained relatively steady \nbetween 2006 and 2012", subtitle = "Total pills shipped to Logan County by year", caption = "Source: DEA ARCOS database, via Washington Post") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(2006, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012)) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = comma)

# The number of pills shipped to Logan County increased by about 400,000 each year from 2006 to 2008, remained about the same in 2009, fell by about 600,000 in 2010, increased by half a million in 2011 and then fell back near the 2010 rate in 2012.

Task: Build an exploratory visualization to show how year-over-year pill totals in Logan County, West Virginia between 2006 and 2012 compare to five other West Virginia counties with high levels of opioid shipments. It should have the following attributes: * Chart Type: six small multiple bar charts, arranged in a 3 x 2 grid. There should be one bar chart per county. * Counties: one chart per county for the following counties: Kanawha, Cabell, Mingo, Raleigh, Logan and Wood. * Axes: years on the x axis, pill totals on the y axis, with proper axis labels. The number for each year should be shown. Put commas in the pill totals on the y axis, so theyre readable. Rotate the year labels so theyre readable.
* Text: put a descriptive title, subtitle and source line. The title should describe the main takeaway.

You should also write up a few sentences explaining the trends in a bit more detail.

# Create new table for pills shipped to West Virginia
wv_pills_per_year <- arcos_county_pills_per_year %>%
  filter(buyer_state == "WV", (buyer_county %in% c("KANAWHA", "CABELL", "MINGO", "RALEIGH","LOGAN", "WOOD"))) %>%
  select(buyer_county, year, dosage_unit)
# Create bar chart for each of the six counties
  ggplot(wv_pills_per_year) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", aes(year, dosage_unit, fill=buyer_county)) +
  labs(x="Year", y="Total pills", title="Steady rise in opioids in three West Virginia counties, \nrise and fall over time in three others ", subtitle = "Total pills per year shipped to Cabell, Kanawha, Logan,\nMingo, Raleigh and Wood counties", caption = "Source: DEA ARCOS database, via Washington Post", fill="County") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(2006, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012)) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = comma) +
  facet_wrap(nrow=2, . ~ buyer_county) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  guides(fill="none")

# The number of pills shipped to Kanawha, Raleigh and Wood counties steadily rose between 2006 and 2012, based on the trends seen in their bar charts. Cabell and Logan saw no major rises or falls during the years tracked. Mingo increased from 2006 to 2008, fell drastically between 2008 and 2010 and then remained relatively consistent through 2012.

Task (This one is more challenging): Build a scatterplot that explores the relationship between the following two factors for Maryland counties: the pills per person rate (not total pills, but pills per person) for a county in 2012 and the countys median household income in 2012.

It should have the following attributes: * each point labeled with the county name. * a blue line of best fit running through the data showing the trend line.
* a title that explains what youre seeing in the data. Is there a trend?

To get the data were going to use for median household income, were going to use the tidycensus package in R, which allows us to pull data directly from the U.S. Census API.

Heres the code youll need to pull it in.

#Get Median Household Income Data for each Maryland County from Tidycensus 
# Help using TidyCensus, including how to find variables of interest. https://walkerke.github.io/tidycensus/articles/basic-usage.html

# Define census api key.  I'm including mine here.  You may need to get your own. https://api.census.gov/data/key_signup.html

census_api_key("549950d36c22ff16455fe196bbbd01d63cfbe6cf")

# Store a table with the median household income value for each county using the get_acs() function.  ACS is short for American Community Survey, one of two main census products. In the table that's loaded in, the :estimate" is the median household income for that county, averaged over 5 years ending in 2012. 

county_median_household_income <- get_acs(geography = "county", variables = c("B19013_001"), survey="acs5", year = 2012)

# How did I get the variables?  I pulled in a table from the tidycensus package that lists all of the thousands of variables available through the census.  Load the table below and view it.  Use filters in the R Viewer window to find things you might want to use later. You can also find table and variable numbers at https://data.census.gov/cedsci/.

acs_variables <- load_variables(2012, "acs5", cache = TRUE)

# Filter just for Maryland counties
md_county_median_household_income <- county_median_household_income %>%
  filter(str_detect(NAME, ", Maryland"))
# Create new object that only returns data about pills sent to Maryland counties in 2012
maryland_pills_2012 <- arcos_county_pills_per_year %>%
  filter(buyer_state == "MD", year=="2012") %>%
  select(buyer_county, year, dosage_unit, countyfips)
# Create object that only returns data about the population of Maryland counties in 2012
maryland_population_2012 <- county_population(key = key) %>%
  clean_names() %>%
  filter(buyer_state == "MD", year=="2012") %>%
  select(county_name, population, countyfips)
# Join Maryland pills and population 2012 datasets 
maryland_2012 <- maryland_pills_2012 %>%
  inner_join(maryland_population_2012, by=("countyfips")) %>%
  select(buyer_county, dosage_unit, population, countyfips)
# Rename GEOID in county median household table
md_income_fips <- md_county_median_household_income %>%
  mutate(countyfips=GEOID)
# Join pills per person and income
  maryland_pills_income <- md_income_fips %>%
  inner_join(maryland_2012, by="countyfips") %>%
  mutate(rate = (dosage_unit/population))
  #view(maryland_pills_income)
# Create scatter plot of pills per person relative to median county income in 2012
ggplot(maryland_pills_income) +
  geom_point(aes(rate, estimate)) +
  labs(x="Pills per person", y="Median income", title="Counties with lower median incomes received more opioid pills\nper person in Maryland in 2012", caption = "Source: DEA ARCOS database, via Washington Post", fill="buyer_county") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = comma) +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = comma) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  geom_smooth(aes(rate, estimate), method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  geom_text_repel(aes(rate, estimate, label=buyer_county))

# Create object that contains only Logan County data
philadelphia_pills_per_year <- arcos_county_pills_per_year %>%

  scale_y_continuous(labels = comma)

# Philadelphia received a massive number of pills during the period tracked by the ARCOS database -- almost 70 million by 2012. The number of pills per year steadily increased over this seven-year span. Seeing the change over time prompts many questions to look into further: Was no one catching on to how extreme the opioid epidemic was in the city during this time? Did any pharmacies get in trouble? How do these rates correlate to Point in Time trends during these years?
